Consider a regular 180-gon. In any triangulation, each side of the polygon is a side of exactly one triangle in the triangulation. In a regular 180-gon each polygon interior angle at a vertex is 179°, so the central small angle subtending one side (the exterior angle at a vertex) is 1°. Equivalently, each triangle that uses a polygon side contributes exactly one 1° angle at the polygon vertex incident to that side. Therefore the total number of 1° angles across all triangles in any triangulation equals the number of polygon sides, 180.

Each triangulation has n-2 = 178 triangles, so the expected number of 1° angles in a uniformly chosen triangle is 180/178 = 90/89. Thus a = 90 and b = 89, and 100a + b = 100·90 + 89 = 9089.

Final answer: \boxed{9089}
